A group of 5 specimens (2 mature & 3 immature) growing in an oak grove just a few yards away from Baorangia bicolor of obs 282994.
The characteristic chicken bouillon odor led to a confident field ID despite the fact that collectively this group displayed some traits more typical of the bicolor group.
The upturned post-mature fruitbody had a cap diameter of 16.5 cm (6.5"); the other old one was even larger. The flesh was bright lemon yellow in the stipe and paler in the cap (almost white in the old cap), typically bluing only above the tube or entirely in the cap; the stipe flesh blued erratically only in small, disjunct areas bordering the surface. The cap thickness/tube length ratio in one of the young fruitbodies was 9:1 (18mm/2mm).

Chemical Tests:
KOH = amber yellow on cap (young & old); muddy orange-brown on flesh (young & old)
NH4OH = light muddy yellow (young) and dark pink with a blue aura around the drop quickly resolving muddy yellow (old) on the pellicle; erased bluing then darker yellow, quickly resolving pale bluish-gray on flesh (young)

Spore Data: A spore print was obtained from the old specimen.
[10/1/1], mounted in 5% KOH and measured only in side-view (hilar appendage to the side).
L x W = 8.4-11.6 × 3.3-4.7 μm, L x W = 9.8 × 3.8 μm. The vast majority of observed spore lengths were in the 8.8-10.2 μm range. I didn’t see any spores longer than 11.6 μm. Q = 2.44-2.80, Q = 2.61. Smooth and greenish, with a large oval-shaped oil droplet; oblong and subfusiform/slightly inequilateral in side-view (dorsiventral) with a very shallow suprahilar plage. Reported spore dimensions for B. pallidoroseus in Bessetes’ NAB/BENA = 9-12 × 3.5-5.5 μm.

Discussion: Overall this fine collection looks a bit different from my benchmark pallidoroseus (obs 103977, obs 210760 and obs 282668 – all collected from the same spot in different years) in that it sports more pallid color in fresh and young fruitbodies, a bluing pileipellis (when young), yellow stipes in the upper ~1/4 length, and a smoother pore transition into the stipe seen in one fruitbody – the latter being more characteristic of bicolor. The post mature fruitbodies are almost indistinguishable from old bicolor other than having the characteristic odor. The observed morphological plasticity is likely a reflection of phenotypic differences typically seen within populations structures of this species, or it might be indicative of a group of closely-related taxa. With regard to the latter notion, compare with Boletus pallidoroseus of obs 247881, which was also sequenced.

results.notes: A low rise wall separates the sidewalk from the dense vegetation. These four mushrooms were on the vegetation side, so close to the wall that the caps touched the wall. The three smaller mushrooms were together and I was able to include the “roots”. The larger one was two meters away. To my untrained nose, they smell like a flavorful, edible mushroom such as shiitake.

These white specimens were growing together so tightly that when I tried to extract the largest, the smaller one dislodged. There was a third, much smaller specimen in the same clump. But, it didn’t dislodge. To my untrained eye, the cap had not fully opened, so I left it.

The area is a kempt lawn outside the wall of a large event center. It is raised from the sidewalk, so there is no foot traffic. The ground is sloped, and some tree roots are exposed in some places. I don’t know what kind of tree. The tree is alive. The clump happened to be growing at a 45 degree angle from under an exposed root. To my untrained eye, it was not connected to the root. The root wasn’t damaged or rotting.

Observado en Cerro El Venado, altura entre 500 – 600 msnm; bosque húmedo pre montano (bh-PM), precipitación mínima de 15 – 25 mm en los meses de enero y diciembre, precipitación máxima 350 mm y 300 mm en los meses de mayo, junio y julio, con menos de 60 mm de lluvia en el mes más seco y precipitación anual superior a 1270 mm. Los máximos valores de temperatura no sobrepasan los 36 °C y los mínimos valores no logran bajar los 19 °C que se presentan en febrero y en julio, respectivamente. Temperatura media anual mayor de 20 °C, con una estación seca y una lluviosa bien definidas (Bustamante, et al 2013). Yopal cuenta con una extensión de 2595 km, Altura media: 390 msnm y una Población Total de 146 204 hab. (2005)

-Cuenta con valores mínimos de humedad relativa a inicio del año (65%), y valores más altos en junio, julio, agosto y septiembre (90-85%), pluviosidad entre 2000 y 4000 mm y temperatura promedio mayor de 24 °C, con amplitud de temperatura máxima de 8 °C, (DANE, 1999; Castro & Sosa, 2017)

-Se observan arboles representativos como Yarumo (Cecropia spp), Cedro (Cedrela odorata), Nauno (Albizzia guachepele), Cañafistol (Cassia moschata), Flor blanco (Tabebuia orinocensis), Uña de gato (Cynodon dactylon), entre otras.
